  "prompt": "How pancreatic cancer is treated?",
  "response": "Pancreatic cancer treatment depends on various factors, including the stage of the disease, the patient's overall health, and the specific characteristics of the tumor. Common treatment options include:\n\n1. **Surgery**: If the cancer is detected early and is localized, surgical options such as the Whipple procedure (pancreaticoduodenectomy), distal pancreatectomy, or total pancreatectomy may be considered. These procedures aim to remove the tumor and a margin of healthy tissue.\n\n2. **Chemotherapy**: This is commonly used for pancreatic cancer and may be administered before surgery (neoadjuvant therapy), after surgery (adjuvant therapy), or as the primary treatment if surgery is not an option. Common chemotherapy regimens include combinations of drugs such as gemcitabine and nab-paclitaxel or FOLFIRINOX.\n\n3. **Radiation therapy**: Often used in conjunction with surgery or chemotherapy, radiation therapy can help to kill cancer cells and shrink tumors. It may be applied before surgery (to make the tumor smaller) or after to eliminate remaining cancer cells.\n\n4. **Targeted therapy**: Some patients may benefit from targeted therapies that focus on specific genetic mutations or characteristics of their cancer. For example, drugs such as erlotinib may be used in certain cases.\n\n5. **Immunotherapy**: In select patients, immunotherapy may be an option, mainly if the cancer has specific genetic markers (like MSI-high or dMMR).\n\n6. **Palliative care**: For advanced pancreatic cancer, where curative treatment is not possible, palliative care focuses on relieving symptoms and improving quality of life. This may include pain management, nutritional support, and psychological assistance.\n\n7. **Clinical trials**: Some patients may have the option to participate in clinical trials exploring new treatments or combinations of therapies that are not yet widely available.\n\nDecisions regarding treatment should be made collaboratively by the patient and their healthcare team, considering the specific circumstances of the disease and the patient's preferences and overall health. Regular follow-up and monitoring are essential for managing pancreatic cancer effectively.",
